John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
The Scottish independent schools maintain a curriculum of academic excellence and this continued in 2018 with another series of outstanding exam results, strengthened by individual and collective success in sport, art, music and other collective efforts.
With over 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), aim to provide the best level of service to their students and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare students for further higher education, chosen careers and their place in the world as global citizens.
As an education sector capable of developing and adopting a personalised school curriculum, we note that modern languages continue to be a popular and required subject within schools.
Nelson Mandela said: "If you speak to a man in a language he understands, the message will reach his brain.
If you speak to him in his mother tongue, the message will reach his heart."
This is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely on the English only if we want to build trust relations with people from other countries.
From the results of this year's exams, we can observe that the languages are at the top of the rankings, with the highest percentages of success within the independent schools.
68% of pupils who have studied foreign languages have received the most votes.
The data, collected from the 74 SCIS member schools, showed that 72% of the students received the highest vote with praise in Chinese, while 72% of those who studied German, 69% of those who studied French and 63% of those who studied Spanish received the highest vote.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland are promoting foreign languages as fundamental skills for children and young people, who will undoubtedly need them in the future.
At present, languages, as a choice of subject, are considered at the same level as STEM materials (science, technology, technology and mathematics) in the curricula of independent institutions and elsewhere.
A survey conducted by the UK Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 found that the reasons that employees have indicated for the difficulty in covering jobs are attributable in 17% of cases to a lack of language skills.
For this reason, language skills are becoming increasingly essential to prepare young people for their future careers.
With more and more job opportunities requiring language knowledge, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the career chosen, if you have learned a second language, you will have an effective advantage in the future with a life skills like this.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries will automatically lead a multilingual person to competition.
According to a survey of YouGov among over 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75% were unable to speak a foreign language at a level sufficient to be able to hold a conversation and French was the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage, 15%.
This is why investing in language teaching is so important for children today.
Knowledge of multiple languages, particularly those of developing economies, will provide children with a better chance of finding a valid employment.
In Scotland, each school will differ in the languages taught.
Several schools will focus on the most classical modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered the most important for the United Kingdom by looking at 2020, such as Mandarin Chinese or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interest, there will always be different languages to choose from in independent schools, with the specialized teaching staff in this area.
The Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare children and provide them with the skills they need for success, regardless of their future.
It is not possible at this time to deny, in a global trading system, that languages continue to be fundamental to the future of the country, and that must be reflected in teaching.
In fact, modern languages should be considered "international communicative powers."
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence for young people in Scotland.
We have to do this.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
