"Without confidence in the US there will be no security in our national security and in these circumstances we absolutely refuse to disarm unilaterally first."
Although Ri has re-used the complaints concerning Washington's resistance to "staged" denuclearization with which North Korea would be rewarded on the basis of gradual actions, his statement was important because it did not in all reject unilateral denuclearization as already done in the past by Pyongyang.
He referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong One and Donald Trump during the first absolute meeting between a U.S. President-in-Office and a North Korean leader, held in Singapore on 12 June, when Kim committed to working towards the "Korean peninsula denuclearization", while Trump promised guarantees of North Korean security.
North Korea sought a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean war, but the United States said that Pyongyang must give up its nuclear weapons first.
Washington has also opposed appeals to ease the strict international sanctions imposed on North Korea.
"The USA insists on the need to "first have a denuclearisation" and to increase the level of pressure with sanctions to achieve their purpose in a coercive manner and even oppose the "declaration of the end of war," Ri said.
