Harvard students take a course on how to get enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year pushed all its students to sleep more in an attempt to contrast the growing virile culture of studying for whole nights fed by caffeine.
A university scholar has found that the students of the number one university in the world often have no idea of the basic concepts of taking care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, has developed the course, which he considers to be the first of its kind in the USA.
He had the idea to start the course after a conference that had given the impact of lack of sleep on learning.
"At the end a girl came to me and said, 'Why am I only told this now, when I am in the last year?'
He said no one had ever told her anything about the importance of sleep, which surprised me very much," he told The Telegraph.
The course, delivered for the first time this year, explains to students the essential concepts of how good sleep habits can help academic and athletic performance as well as improve general well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and general director of health services at the university, said that the university decided to introduce the course after finding that students suffered from a severe lack of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course provides for a series of interactive activities.
In a section there is the image of a bedroom, where students can select coffee cups, curtains, gym shoes and books to know the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performances are influenced by the lack of sleep, and the importance of an evening routine.
In another section, participants are explained how long-term sleeplessness can increase the risk of heart attacks, stroke, depression and cancer.
A map of the campus, with interactive icons, therefore encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
"We know that the behavior of students will not change immediately.
But we believe that they have a right to know, just as you have the right to know the effects on the health of the choice of smoking cigarettes," added Prof. Czeisler.
The culture of pride linked to the "white night to study", still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and increasing pressure on students lead to a lack of sleep being a growing problem.
Sleeping long enough and with a sleep of good quality should be the "secret weapon" of students to fight stress, fatigue, anxiety, explained and even should serve to avoid fattening because the lack of sleep brings the brain into mode of inedia, making people constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian student enrolled in the faculty of chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler develop the course, after taking one of his lessons last year during his first year at Harvard.
He explained that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to promote a course aimed at the entire campus.
The next step, hopefully, will be to ask all graduate students to follow a similar curriculum before joining this competitive institute.
Prof Czeisler advised students to set up an alarm clock for when they have to go to bed, as well as for when they have to wake up, and to be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED lights, which can send in tilt the circadian rhythm, leading to sleeping problems.
