Tim Berners-Lee, inventor of the World Wide Web, is launching a startup that seeks to compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest technology legend project, Inrupt, is a company that comes from Berners-Lee's open source Solid platform.
Solid allows users to choose where to store their data and what people can access and to what information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that the intent hidden behind Inrupt is "to dominate the world".
"We have to do it now," he said of the startup.
"It's a historic moment."
The app uses Solid technology to allow people to create their own "online personal data storage" or a POD.
It can include lists of contacts, things to do, calendars, music libraries and other personal and professional instruments.
It's like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify were all available on one browser and at the same time.
The uniqueness of the online personal data store is that it is completely at the choice of the user who can have access to what type of information.
The company calls it "personal empowerment through data."
The idea for Inrupt, according to John Bruce, CEO of the company, is to provide adequate resources, processes and skills to make Solid accessible to everyone.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, some developers in the staff hired to work on the project, and a community of volunteer programmers.
Starting this week, technology programmers around the world will be able to give life to their decentralized apps using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said that he and his team will not tell "Facebook and Google whether or not to introduce a complete change where their business models are completely out of place from one day to the next.
"We're not asking for their permission."
In a post on Medium published on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that "Inrupt's mission is to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem that help protect the integrity and quality of the new web built from Solid".
In 1994 Berners-Lee transformed the Internet when he founded the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months Berners-Lee has been an influential voice in the debate on net neutrality.
Even after the launch of Inrupt, Berners-Lee will remain the Founder and Director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
"I'm incredibly optimistic about this new era of the web," Berners-Lee added.
Bernard Vann: Commemorated the Ecclesiastical of the Great War with Victoria Cross
The only clergyman of the Church of England to be rewarded with a Victoria Cross during the First World War as a fighter was commemorated in his hometown after 100 years.
Lieutenant Colonel, Reverend Bernard Vann, won the award on September 29, 1918 in the attack on Bellenglise and Lehaucourt.
However, four days later he was killed by a sniper and never knew he had achieved the highest level of British military honor.
Saturday at a parade in Rushden, Northamptonshire, his two grandchildren inaugurated a commemorative plaque.
One of his grandchildren, Michael Vann, said it was "magnificically symbolic" that the stone would be inaugurated exactly 100 years after his grandfather's award-winning prowess.
According to the London Gazette, on September 29, 1918, Lieutenant Colonel Van led his battalion beyond the Saint-Quentin Canal "through a dense fog, under heavy fire from the field and war machines".
Then he rushed towards the line of fire and with the "greatest gallantry" made the line advance before running with a single-handed cannon and landing three of the detachment.
Lieutenant Colonel Vann was killed by a German sniper on October 4, 1918 - just a month before the end of the war.
Michael Vann, 72, said his grandfather's actions were "something I know I can never be up to and something that makes me more humble."
He and his brother, Dr. James Vann, also deposited a crown of flowers after the parade, led by the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
Michael Vann said that "he felt truly honoured to play a role in the parade" and added "the value of a true hero is shown by the support that will be given him by many people".
