Desert Island Discs: Tom Daley felt "inferior" due to sexuality
The Olympic swimmer Tom Daley says he grew up feeling inferior to anyone because of his sexuality - but this gave him the motivation to succeed.
The 24-year-old said he didn't realize, until he got to high school, that "not everyone is like me".
Speaking on the first episode of Desert Island Discs by Radio 4, presented by Lauren Laverne, he said he had made his voice heard about gay rights to give "hope" to others.
He also said that having become a parent meant that he cared less about winning the Olympics.
The usual presenter of the old-time program, Kirsty Young, took a series of months off for illness.
Presenting himself as an outcast in the first Laverne program, Daley said he felt "less" than anyone else as he grew up because "he was not socially acceptable that he liked both boys and girls."
He said, "Today, the feeling of feeling less than, and of feeling different, was the things that really gave me the strength and the energy to be successful."
He wanted to try to be "something," he said, so as not to disappoint anyone if they had by chance discovered his sexuality.
The two-time bronze medal at the Olympics has become a high profile LGBT activist and has used his face in this year's Commonwealth Games to appeal to more countries to decriminalize homosexuality.
He said he had his voice heard because he felt lucky to be able to live openly without consequences and wanted to give "hope" to others.
The three-time World Champion said that the fact of falling in love with a man - the American director Dustin Lance Black, who met in 2013- "has caught me in surprise".
Daley married Oscar's winner, who's 20 years older than him last year, but said the age difference was never a problem.
"When he passed so many in young age" - he went to his first Olympics when he was 14 and his father died of cancer three years later - he said it was hard to find someone of the same age who had experienced similar highs and lows.
The two became parents in June, of a child named Robert Ray Black-Daley, and Daley said his "whole perspective" has changed.
"If you had asked me last year, it was all about the fact that 'I had to win a gold medal'," he said.
"You know, there are more important things than Olympic gold medals.
My Olympic gold medal is Robbie."
His son bears the same name as his father Robert, who died in 2011 at the age of 40 years after he was diagnosed with brain cancer.
Daley said that his father had not accepted the fact that he was going to die and that one of the last things he asked was if they already had tickets for London 2012 - because he wanted to be in the front row.
"I couldn't tell him 'you won't be around here so I could be in the front row, Dad'," he said.
"I was holding his hand when he stopped breathing and until he actually stopped and died, I had not yet realized that he was not invincible," he said.
The following year Daley competed in the 2012 Olympics, winning bronze.
"I only knew it was what I had dreamed for my whole life - swimming in front of a home audience in the Olympic Games, there was no better feeling," he said.
This also inspired the choice of his first song - Proud by Heather Small - which had a special meaning for him in preparing for the Olympics and still makes him goose skin.
Desert Island Discs is on BBC Radio 4 on Sunday at 11:15 BST.
