Germany's new military ship has been postponed again
According to local media, the last frigate of the German military navy was to be commissioned in 2014 to replace the old military ships of the times of the cold war, but there will not be at least until next year due to faulty systems and an impennade of costs.
The Rheinland-Pfalz commission, the Admiral of the new frigates of the Baden-Württemberg class, was postponed until the first half of 2019, according to the newspaper Die Zeit citing a military spokesman.
The ship should have joined the military navy in 2014, but worrying issues following delivery have tormented the fate of the ambitious project.
The four Baden-Württemberg class ships ordered by the Military Navy in 2007 will replace the old Bremen class ships.
They will have a powerful cannon, a range of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles as well as some hidden technologies, such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic markings.
Other important features include longer maintenance periods, as it should be possible to use new frigates up to two years away from national ports.
However, the continuing delays imply that the innovative warships, which is said to allow Germany to project its power oversea, will already become obsolete when they enter service, notes the Die Zeit.
The unfortunate F-125 frigate reported last year, when the German military navy officially refused to commission the ship and returned it to the ship yard Blohm & Voss of Hamburg.
It was the first time the Navy returned a ship to the builder after delivery.
Little was known about the reasons for the return, but the German media have noticed a number of crucial "software and hardware defects" that have made the ship useless if used in a combat mission.
The shortcomings in the software were particularly important as the ships of the Baden-Württemberg class will be managed by a crew of about 120 sailors, just half of the staff of the oldest ships of the Bremen class.
In addition, it has emerged that the ship weighs heavily, and this reduces its performance and limits the military Navy's ability to add future updates.
It is believed that the Rheinland-Pfalz, of 7,000 tons, is twice as heavy as the ships of similar classes used by the Germans in the Second World War.
Apart from bad hardware, also the cost of the entire project (including crew training) is becoming an important issue.
It seems that it has reached EUR 3.1 billion (US$ 3.6 billion) from the initials EUR 2.2 billion.
The problems involved in the new frigates become of particular importance in the light of recent alarms concerning the reduction of German naval power.
At the beginning of the year, Hans-Peter Bartels, a parliamentary commissioner for the Armed Forces, admitted that the military navy actually "scarse of ships capable of being employed".
The official stated that the issue has deteriorated considerably over time, since the old unarmed ships have not been replaced by new ships.
His regret is that none of the Baden-Württemberg frigates could join the military navy.
The National Trust watches over the secret life of bats
New research carried out in a Scottish Highland estate aims to reveal how bats use vision to obtain food.
It is hoped that discoveries can shed light on the behaviour of the only flying mammals and guide future protection activities.
The study of scientists at the National Trust for Scotland will follow common and soprano bats, as well as brown earring and Daubenton bats at the Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in key places around the property to track bat activities during the season.
The NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile investigations with the use of portable detectors.
Analysis of the sounds recorded by an expert will determine the frequency of callbacks of bats and how each species behaves.
A habitat map and a report will then be produced to create a detailed picture of their behaviour.
Rob Dewar, advisor for nature protection for the NTS, hopes that the results can reveal which habitat areas are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to determine the benefits of habitat management, such as the creation of meadows, and how to keep the best forests for bats and other related species.
The population of bats in Scotland and the United Kingdom has declined considerably in the last century.
Bats are at risk due to the construction and development work that affects trespolis and ruins the habitat.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a threat, as well as mosquito paper and some chemical treatments of building materials, as well as attacks by domestic cats.
Bats aren't really blind.
However, because of their night hunting habits, their ears are more useful than the eyes when it comes to catching a prey.
They use a sophisticated eco-location technique to identify insects and obstacles to their trajectory.
The NTS, responsible for the care of over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, takes bats very seriously.
Ten qualified experts regularly conduct investigations, inspect the truces and sometimes carry out rescues.
The organization has even established the first reserve of Scotland intended only for bats at the estate of Threave, in the region of Dumfries and Galloway, which houses eight of the ten species of bats of Scotland.
The estate manager, David Thompson, claims that the property is the ideal territory.
"Here in Threave we have a vast area for bats," he said.
"We have ancient buildings, many centuries-old trees and good habitat.
But there's a lot about bats we don't know yet, so the work we do here and in the other properties will help us to understand more about their growth needs."
He stressed the importance of controlling bats before conducting maintenance within the properties as it is possible that the involuntary destruction of a single maternal trespolus could kill up to 400 females and children, possibly sweeping away an entire local population.
The bats are protected and it is illegal to kill them, harass them, disturb them or destroy their tresples.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish Head of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help.
He said, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats and for many of our species we don't know how they pass on their populations."
