Fisheries and agriculture are the main sources of support for the economy of the Central Sulawesi province and especially the coastal region of Donggala.
Nickel extraction is also an important activity in the province, but is mostly concentrated in Morowali, on the opposite coast of Sulawesi.
Palu and Donggala have been affected several times by tsunamis in the last 100 years, according to Indonesia's Disaster Mitigation Agency.
In 1938, a tsunami killed more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of homes in Donggala.
Another tsunami hit the western area of Donggala in 1996 killing nine people.
Indonesia is located in the seismic zone called the Pacific fire belt and is often hit by earthquakes.
Here are some of the earthquakes and the strongest tsunamis of recent years:
2004: On 26 December a very strong earthquake on the western coast of the province of Aceh north of Sumatra caused a tsunami that struck 14 countries killing, along the coast of the Indian Ocean, 226,000 people, of which over half of Aceh.
2005: a series of strong earthquakes struck the western coast of Sumatra between the end of March and the beginning of April.
