Syria is "ready" for the return of refugees, supports the Foreign Minister
Syria says it is ready to return refugees and is seeking help to rebuild the country devastated by over seven years of war.
In the face of the UN General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said that the conditions of the country are improving.
"Today the situation on the territory is more stable and secure thanks to the progress made in the fight against terrorism," he said.
The government continues to recover areas destroyed by terrorists to restore normality.
Now there are all the conditions for the voluntary return of refugees to the country who had to leave because of terrorism and the unilateral economic measures that affected their daily lives and livelihoods.
According to the United Nations estimate, more than 5.5 million Syrians have left the country since the start of the war in 2011.
Another six million still living in Syria are in need of humanitarian aid.
Al-Moualem said that the Syrian regime will gladly accept assistance to rebuild the devastated country.
But he stressed that he would not accept any subordinate aid under conditions or by those countries that supported the insurrection.
